<br>
It's great for vector animation, and but if you want TV-like animation, best to go with an actual animation program.<br>
<br>
I love Flash, but it's more of a web-based, programmable software than frame-by-frame animation package. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ugothicchaos.showPublicProfile?language=EN>gothic chaos</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(3/24/02 9:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=568.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A Little Help...</span><hr size=1> I know your going for animation, but to begin with, you have to write as much as you can down.<br>
<br>
For instance:&quot;where will this take place?&quot;, &quot;in what time period?&quot;,&quot;how many main characters are there going to be?&quot; and &quot;whats the main objective of the main characters?&quot;<br>
<br>
As tedious as this may seem, its helps out a lot more when things start to become more fleshed-out. A lot of times when people don't take the time to do this their story can become confusing, boring, or repetative.<br>
<br>
I'm sorry to say though, I don't know of any good animation programs. I'm still sort of stuck in my still life stage. <br>
<br>
